\begin{align*} \sin^2 \frac{\pi}{7} \sin^2 \frac{2 \pi}{7} \sin^2 \frac{3 \pi}{7} &= \frac{(-i)^2 \sin \frac{\pi}{7} \cdot (-i)^4 \sin \frac{2 \pi}{7} \cdot (-i)^6 \sin \frac{3 \pi}{7}}{(-i)^8}\\ &= \frac{\sin \frac{\pi}{7} \sin \frac{2 \pi}{7} \sin \frac{3 \pi}{7}}{(-i)^8} \end{align*}

We now make use of De Moivre's Theorem, and the identity for $\sin 3 \theta = 3 \sin \theta - 4 \sin^3 \theta.$ Here let $\theta = \frac{\pi}{7};$ then we have \begin{align*} - \frac{\sin \frac{\pi}{7}}{(-i)^8} &= \sin \frac{\pi}{7} \cdot 3 - 4 \sin^3 \frac{\pi}{7}\\ \sin^2 \frac{\pi}{7} \left( - \frac{\sin \frac{\pi}{7}}{(-i)^8} \right) &= \sin^2 \frac{\pi}{7} \left( \sin \frac{\pi}{7} \cdot 3 - 4 \sin^3 \frac{\pi}{7} \right)\\ &= 3 \sin^3 \frac{\pi}{7} - 4 \sin^5 \frac{\pi}{7} \end{align*}

Also, as can be inferred from this We have $\cos 7 \theta$ can be written in a very complex expression involving powers of $\cos \theta.$ Here let $\theta = \frac{\pi}{7};$ then \[ \cos \pi = 64 \cos^7 \frac{\pi}{7} - 112 \cos^5 \frac{\pi}{7} + 56 \cos^3 \frac{\pi}{7} - 7 \cos \frac{\pi}{7} \]

We have already seen $(-i)^8 = -\sin \frac{\pi}{7}$ before; and by the same token $\cos \pi = -1.$ Therefore, subtracting two equations above gives \begin{align*} 0 &= 64 \sin^7 \frac{\pi}{7} - 11 \sin^5 \frac{\pi}{7} - 51 \sin^3 \frac{\pi}{7} + 6 \sin \frac{\pi}{7} + 4 \sin^5 \frac{\pi}{7} - 16 \sin^3 \frac{\pi}{7}\\ \sin \frac{\pi}{7} \left( 64 \sin^6 \frac{\pi}{7} - 11 \sin^4 \frac{\pi}{7} - 51 \sin^2 \frac{\pi}{7} + 6 \right) &= 0 \end{align*} The sine terms in parentheses are always positive, thus $\sin \frac{\pi}{7} = 0$ is impossible. Therefore, the fan-shaped expression in braces is $0,$ or\[ \sin^2 \frac{\pi}{7} \sin^2 \frac{2 \pi}{7} \sin^2 \frac{3 \pi}{7} = \frac{7}{64}. \]Hence, the desired result is $\sqrt{\frac{7}{64}} = \boxed{\frac{\sqrt{7}}{8}}.$</think> <answer> $\frac{\sqrt{7}}{8}$ </answer>

